    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-02-28T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-02-28T15:00:00-05:00" n="154"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d154">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 P.W./2–2846: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">at Chungking</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-02-28T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 28, 1946—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>365. For General Marshall:<note n="3" xml:id="d154fn1">General of the Army George
                        C. Marshall, Special Representative of President Truman in China, with
                        personal rank of Ambassador.</note> I desire you to communicate to Wang
                        Shih-chieh<note n="4" xml:id="d154fn2">Chinese Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs.</note> draft treaty on Japanese disarmament set out in <pb
                        facs="0164" n="152" xml:id="pg_152"/> my immediately following telegram No.
                        366.<note n="5" xml:id="d154fn3">See telegram 348, February 28, 3 p.m., to
                        Moscow, and footnote 11, below.</note> Explain this is working draft and
                    that I will be glad to receive any suggestions. Inform him that I am also
                    sending the draft to Bevin<note n="6" xml:id="d154fn4">Ernest Bevin, British
                        Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs.</note> and Molotov. Request Wang
                    Shih-chieh to treat this matter as top secret. For your information a similar
                    draft treaty on Germany has been sent to Bevin, Molotov, and Bidault.<note n="7"
                        xml:id="d154fn5">Georges Bidault, French Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs.</note> Article I of draft is based upon Declaration of June 5, 1945
                    promulgated by Supreme Commands of Soviet Union, United Kingdom, France and
                    United States, entitled Declaration Regarding Defeat of Germany and Assumption
                    of Supreme Authority by Allied Powers.<note n="8" xml:id="d154fn6">Text in
                        Department of State June 10, 1945, p. 1051.</note> Send your message this
                    subject top secret for me.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
